subject: http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/date
object: Date may be used to express temporal information at any level of granularity.  Recommended practice is to express the date, date/time, or period of time according to ISO 8601-1 [[ISO 8601-1](https://www.iso.org/iso-8601-date-and-time-format.html)] or a published profile of the ISO standard, such as the W3C Note on Date and Time Formats [[W3CDTF](https://www.w3.org/TR/NOTE-datetime)] or the Extended Date/Time Format Specification [[EDTF](http://www.loc.gov/standards/datetime/)].  If the full date is unknown, month and year (YYYY-MM) or just year (YYYY) may be used. Date ranges may be specified using ISO 8601 period of time specification in which start and end dates are separated by a '/' (slash) character.  Either the start or end date may be missing.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/creator

subject: http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/coverage
object: Spatial topic and spatial applicability may be a named place or a location specified by its geographic coordinates. Temporal topic may be a named period, date, or date range. A jurisdiction may be a named administrative entity or a geographic place to which the resource applies. Recommended practice is to use a controlled vocabulary such as the Getty Thesaurus of Geographic Names [[TGN](https://www.getty.edu/research/tools/vocabulary/tgn/index.html)]. Where appropriate, named places or time periods may be used in preference to numeric identifiers such as sets of coordinates or date ranges.

object: The spatial or temporal topic of the resource, spatial applicability of the resource, or jurisdiction under which the resource is relevant.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/accrualPolicy
object: Recommended practice is to use a value from the Collection Description Accrual Policy Vocabulary [[DCMI-ACCRUALPOLICY](https://dublincore.org/groups/collections/accrual-policy/)].

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/accrualPolicy
object: The policy governing the addition of items to a collection.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/creator
object: An entity responsible for making the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/valid
object: Date (often a range) of validity of a resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/ISO3166
object: The set of codes listed in ISO 3166-1 for the representation of names of countries.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/isRequiredBy
object: This property is intended to be used with non-literal values. This property is an inverse property of Requires.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/alternative
object: The distinction between titles and alternative titles is application-specific.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/references
object: This property is intended to be used with non-literal values. This property is an inverse property of Is Referenced By.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/isReplacedBy
object: A related resource that supplants, displaces, or supersedes the described resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/audience
object: Recommended practice is to use this property with non-literal values from a vocabulary of audience types.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/BibliographicResource
object: A book, article, or other documentary resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/date
object: A point or period of time associated with an event in the lifecycle of the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/MethodOfInstruction
object: A process that is used to engender knowledge, attitudes, and skills.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/RFC5646
object: The set of tags constructed according to RFC 5646 for the identification of languages.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/accrualMethod
object: The method by which items are added to a collection.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/SizeOrDuration
object: Examples include a number of pages, a specification of length, width, and breadth, or a period in hours, minutes, and seconds.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/dateAccepted
object: Date of acceptance of the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/ISO639-2
object: The three-letter alphabetic codes listed in ISO639-2 for the representation of names of languages.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/type
object: The nature or genre of the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/alternative
object: An alternative name for the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/instructionalMethod
object: Instructional Method typically includes ways of presenting instructional materials or conducting instructional activities, patterns of learner-to-learner and learner-to-instructor interactions, and mechanisms by which group and individual levels of learning are measured.  Instructional methods include all aspects of the instruction and learning processes from planning and implementation through evaluation and feedback.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/mediator
object: In an educational context, a mediator might be a parent, teacher, teaching assistant, or care-giver.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/MESH
object: The set of labeled concepts specified by the Medical Subject Headings.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/created
object: Recommended practice is to describe the date, date/time, or period of time as recommended for the property Date, of which this is a subproperty.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/modified
object: Date on which the resource was changed.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/bibliographicCitation
object: A bibliographic reference for the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/conformsTo
object: An established standard to which the described resource conforms.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/ProvenanceStatement
object: Any changes in ownership and custody of a resource since its creation that are significant for its authenticity, integrity, and interpretation.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/date
object: Date may be used to express temporal information at any level of granularity.  Recommended practice is to express the date, date/time, or period of time according to ISO 8601-1 [[ISO 8601-1](https://www.iso.org/iso-8601-date-and-time-format.html)] or a published profile of the ISO standard, such as the W3C Note on Date and Time Formats [[W3CDTF](https://www.w3.org/TR/NOTE-datetime)] or the Extended Date/Time Format Specification [[EDTF](http://www.loc.gov/standards/datetime/)].  If the full date is unknown, month and year (YYYY-MM) or just year (YYYY) may be used. Date ranges may be specified using ISO 8601 period of time specification in which start and end dates are separated by a '/' (slash) character.  Either the start or end date may be missing.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/Standard
object: A reference point against which other things can be evaluated or compared.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/MediaType
object: A file format or physical medium.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/W3CDTF
object: The set of dates and times constructed according to the W3C Date and Time Formats Specification.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/source
object: This property is intended to be used with non-literal values. The described resource may be derived from the related resource in whole or in part. Best practice is to identify the related resource by means of a URI or a string conforming to a formal identification system.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/identifier
object: An unambiguous reference to the resource within a given context.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Service
object: Examples include a photocopying service, a banking service, an authentication service, interlibrary loans, a Z39.50 or Web server.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/MovingImage
object: A series of visual representations imparting an impression of motion when shown in succession.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Text
object: Examples include books, letters, dissertations, poems, newspapers, articles, archives of mailing lists. Note that facsimiles or images of texts are still of the genre Text.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Image
object: A visual representation other than text.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Event
object: Metadata for an event provides descriptive information that is the basis for discovery of the purpose, location, duration, and responsible agents associated with an event. Examples include an exhibition, webcast, conference, workshop, open day, performance, battle, trial, wedding, tea party, conflagration.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Image
object: Examples include images and photographs of physical objects, paintings, prints, drawings, other images and graphics, animations and moving pictures, film, diagrams, maps, musical notation.  Note that Image may include both electronic and physical representations.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/InteractiveResource
object: A resource requiring interaction from the user to be understood, executed, or experienced.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Dataset
object: Examples include lists, tables, and databases.  A dataset may be useful for direct machine processing.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/PhysicalObject
object: Note that digital representations of, or surrogates for, these objects should use Image, Text or one of the other types.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Collection
object: A collection is described as a group; its parts may also be separately described.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/InteractiveResource
object: Examples include forms on Web pages, applets, multimedia learning objects, chat services, or virtual reality environments.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Software
object: Examples include a C source file, MS-Windows .exe executable, or Perl script.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Sound
object: Examples include a music playback file format, an audio compact disc, and recorded speech or sounds.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/StillImage
object: Examples include paintings, drawings, graphic designs, plans and maps. Recommended best practice is to assign the type Text to images of textual materials. Instances of the type Still Image must also be describable as instances of the broader type Image.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Service
object: A system that provides one or more functions.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Software
object: A computer program in source or compiled form.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/PhysicalObject
object: An inanimate, three-dimensional object or substance.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Dataset
object: Data encoded in a defined structure.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Sound
object: A resource primarily intended to be heard.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Text
object: A resource consisting primarily of words for reading.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/MovingImage
object: Examples include animations, movies, television programs, videos, zoetropes, or visual output from a simulation.  Instances of the type Moving Image must also be describable as instances of the broader type Image.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/holdsAccount
object: Indicates an account held by this agent.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/plan
object: A .plan comment, in the tradition of finger and '.plan' files.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/givenName
object: The given name of some person.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/givenname
object: The given name of some person.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/pastProject
object: A project this person has previously worked on.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/mbox
object: A  personal mailbox, ie. an Internet mailbox associated with exactly one owner, the first owner of this mailbox. This is a 'static inverse functional property', in that  there is (across time and change) at most one individual that ever has any particular value for foaf:mbox.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/geekcode
object: A textual geekcode for this person, see http://www.geekcode.com/geek.html

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/topic_interest
object: A thing of interest to this person.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/weblog
object: A weblog of some thing (whether person, group, company etc.).

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/interest
object: A page about a topic of interest to this person.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/nick
object: A short informal nickname characterising an agent (includes login identifiers, IRC and other chat nicknames).

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/membershipClass
object: Indicates the class of individuals that are a member of a Group

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/phone
object: A phone,  specified using fully qualified tel: URI scheme (refs: http://www.w3.org/Addressing/schemes.html#tel).

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/family_name
object: The family name of some person.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/mbox_sha1sum
object: The sha1sum of the URI of an Internet mailbox associated with exactly one owner, the  first owner of the mailbox.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/firstName
object: The first name of a person.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/img
object: An image that can be used to represent some thing (ie. those depictions which are particularly representative of something, eg. one's photo on a homepage).

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/dnaChecksum
object: A checksum for the DNA of some thing. Joke.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/primaryTopic
object: The primary topic of some page or document.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/familyName
object: The family name of some person.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/birthday
object: The birthday of this Agent, represented in mm-dd string form, eg. '12-31'.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/status
object: A string expressing what the user is happy for the general public (normally) to know about their current activity.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/Agent
object: An agent (eg. person, group, software or physical artifact).

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/tipjar
object: A tipjar document for this agent, describing means for payment and reward.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/mbox_sha1sum
object: sha1sum of a personal mailbox URI name

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/fundedBy
object: An organization funding a project or person.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/page
object: A page or document about this thing.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/member
object: Indicates a member of a Group

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/isPrimaryTopicOf
object: A document that this thing is the primary topic of.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/lastName
object: The last name of a person.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/schoolHomepage
object: A homepage of a school attended by the person.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/knows
object: A person known by this person (indicating some level of reciprocated interaction between the parties).

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/gender
object: The gender of this Agent (typically but not necessarily 'male' or 'female').

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/workInfoHomepage
object: A work info homepage of some person; a page about their work for some organization.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/LabelProperty
object: A foaf:LabelProperty is any RDF property with texual values that serve as labels.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/maker
object: An agent that  made this thing.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/age
object: The age in years of some agent.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/publications
object: A link to the publications of this person.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/accountName
object: Indicates the name (identifier) associated with this online account.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/currentProject
object: A current project this person works on.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/focus
object: The underlying or 'focal' entity associated with some SKOS-described concept.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/Project
object: A project (a collective endeavour of some kind).

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/workplaceHomepage
object: A workplace homepage of some person; the homepage of an organization they work for.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/account
object: Indicates an account held by this agent.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/depicts
object: A thing depicted in this representation.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/
object: The Friend of a Friend (FOAF) RDF vocabulary, described using W3C RDF Schema and the Web Ontology Language.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/topic
object: A topic of some page or document.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/accountServiceHomepage
object: Indicates a homepage of the service provide for this online account.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/made
object: Something that was made by this agent.

subject: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/based_near
object: A location that something is based near, for some broadly human notion of near.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#propertyDisjointWith
object: The property that determines that two given properties are disjoint.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#complementOf
object: The property that determines that a given class is the complement of another class.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Annotation
object: The class of annotated annotations for which the RDF serialization consists of an annotated subject, predicate and object.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#someValuesFrom
object: The property that determines the class that an existential property restriction refers to.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#annotatedProperty
object: The property that determines the predicate of an annotated axiom or annotated annotation.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#onClass
object: The property that determines the class that a qualified object cardinality restriction refers to.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#deprecated
object: The annotation property that indicates that a given entity has been deprecated.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#disjointWith
object: The property that determines that two given classes are disjoint.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#qualifiedCardinality
object: The property that determines the cardinality of an exact qualified cardinality restriction.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Axiom
object: The class of annotated axioms for which the RDF serialization consists of an annotated subject, predicate and object.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl
object:
This ontology partially describes the built-in classes and
  properties that together form the basis of the RDF/XML syntax of OWL 2.
  The content of this ontology is based on Tables 6.1 and 6.2
  in Section 6.4 of the OWL 2 RDF-Based Semantics specification,
  available at http://www.w3.org/TR/owl2-rdf-based-semantics/.
  Please note that those tables do not include the different annotations
  (labels, comments and rdfs:isDefinedBy links) used in this file.
  Also note that the descriptions provided in this ontology do not
  provide a complete and correct formal description of either the syntax
  or the semantics of the introduced terms (please see the OWL 2
  recommendations for the complete and normative specifications).
  Furthermore, the information provided by this ontology may be
  misleading if not used with care. This ontology SHOULD NOT be imported
  into OWL ontologies. Importing this file into an OWL 2 DL ontology
  will cause it to become an OWL 2 Full ontology and may have other,
  unexpected, consequences.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#targetValue
object: The property that determines the value of a negative data property assertion.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#allValuesFrom
object: The property that determines the class that a universal property restriction refers to.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#differentFrom
object: The property that determines that two given individuals are different.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#minCardinality
object: The property that determines the cardinality of a minimum cardinality restriction.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#assertionProperty
object: The property that determines the predicate of a negative property assertion.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#minQualifiedCardinality
object: The property that determines the cardinality of a minimum qualified cardinality restriction.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NegativePropertyAssertion
object: The class of negative property assertions.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#equivalentProperty
object: The property that determines that two given properties are equivalent.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#bottomDataProperty
object: The data property that does not relate any individual to any data value.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#targetIndividual
object: The property that determines the object of a negative object property assertion.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#topObjectProperty
object: The object property that relates every two individuals.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#withRestrictions
object: The property that determines the collection of facet-value pairs that define a datatype restriction.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#hasValue
object: The property that determines the individual that a has-value restriction refers to.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#AllDisjointProperties
object: The class of collections of pairwise disjoint properties.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#maxCardinality
object: The property that determines the cardinality of a maximum cardinality restriction.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#maxQualifiedCardinality
object: The property that determines the cardinality of a maximum qualified cardinality restriction.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#unionOf
object: The property that determines the collection of classes or data ranges that build a union.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#incompatibleWith
object: The annotation property that indicates that a given ontology is incompatible with another ontology.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#imports
object: The property that is used for importing other ontologies into a given ontology.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#onDatatype
object: The property that determines the datatype that a datatype restriction refers to.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#disjointUnionOf
object: The property that determines that a given class is equivalent to the disjoint union of a collection of other classes.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#versionInfo
object: The annotation property that provides version information for an ontology or another OWL construct.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#AllDisjointClasses
object: The class of collections of pairwise disjoint classes.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#equivalentClass
object: The property that determines that two given classes are equivalent, and that is used to specify datatype definitions.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#priorVersion
object: The annotation property that indicates the predecessor ontology of a given ontology.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#versionIRI
object: The property that identifies the version IRI of an ontology.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#distinctMembers
object: The property that determines the collection of pairwise different individuals in a owl:AllDifferent axiom.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#members
object: The property that determines the collection of members in either a owl:AllDifferent, owl:AllDisjointClasses or owl:AllDisjointProperties axiom.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#onProperties
object: The property that determines the n-tuple of properties that a property restriction on an n-ary data range refers to.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#propertyChainAxiom
object: The property that determines the n-tuple of properties that build a sub property chain of a given property.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#topDataProperty
object: The data property that relates every individual to every data value.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#datatypeComplementOf
object: The property that determines that a given data range is the complement of another data range with respect to the data domain.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#hasKey
object: The property that determines the collection of properties that jointly build a key.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#cardinality
object: The property that determines the cardinality of an exact cardinality restriction.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#backwardCompatibleWith
object: The annotation property that indicates that a given ontology is backward compatible with another ontology.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#annotatedSource
object: The property that determines the subject of an annotated axiom or annotated annotation.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#hasSelf
object: The property that determines the property that a self restriction refers to.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#sourceIndividual
object: The property that determines the subject of a negative property assertion.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#AllDifferent
object: The class of collections of pairwise different individuals.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#DataRange
object: The class of OWL data ranges, which are special kinds of datatypes. Note: The use of the IRI owl:DataRange has been deprecated as of OWL 2. The IRI rdfs:Datatype SHOULD be used instead.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#onProperty
object: The property that determines the property that a property restriction refers to.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#inverseOf
object: The property that determines that two given properties are inverse.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#oneOf
object: The property that determines the collection of individuals or data values that build an enumeration.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#intersectionOf
object: The property that determines the collection of classes or data ranges that build an intersection.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#bottomObjectProperty
object: The object property that does not relate any two individuals.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#onDataRange
object: The property that determines the data range that a qualified data cardinality restriction refers to.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#sameAs
object: The property that determines that two given individuals are equal.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#annotatedTarget
object: The property that determines the object of an annotated axiom or annotated annotation.

subject: http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#nil
object: The empty list, with no items in it. If the rest of a list is nil then the list has no more items in it.

subject: http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#object
object: The object of the subject RDF statement.

subject: http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#JSON
object: The datatype of RDF literals storing JSON content.

subject: http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#first
object: The first item in the subject RDF list.

subject: http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#direction
object: The base direction component of a CompoundLiteral.

subject: http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML
object: The datatype of RDF literals storing fragments of HTML content

subject: http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#value
object: Idiomatic property used for structured values.

subject: http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#
object: This is the RDF Schema for the RDF vocabulary terms in the RDF Namespace, defined in RDF 1.1 Concepts.

subject: http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#language
object: The language component of a CompoundLiteral.

subject: http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#subject
object: The subject of the subject RDF statement.

subject: http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#langString
object: The datatype of language-tagged string values

subject: http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#rest
object: The rest of the subject RDF list after the first item.

subject: http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type
object: The subject is an instance of a class.

subject: http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#PlainLiteral
object: The class of plain (i.e. untyped) literal values, as used in RIF and OWL 2

subject: http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#predicate
object: The predicate of the subject RDF statement.

subject: http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#CompoundLiteral
object: A class representing a compound literal.

subject: http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#Alt
object: The class of containers of alternatives.

subject: http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#XMLLiteral
object: The datatype of XML literal values.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label
object: A human-readable name for the subject.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy
object: The defininition of the subject resource.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subPropertyOf
object: The subject is a subproperty of a property.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#range
object: A range of the subject property.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#Literal
object: The class of literal values, eg. textual strings and integers.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment
object: A description of the subject resource.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#member
object: A member of the subject resource.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf
object: The subject is a subclass of a class.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#domain
object: A domain of the subject property.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#ContainerMembershipProperty
object:
The class of container membership properties, rdf:_1, rdf:_2, ...,
                    all of which are sub-properties of 'member'.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#seeAlso
object: Further information about the subject resource.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#historyNote
object: A note about the past state/use/meaning of a concept.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#note
object: A general note, for any purpose.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#mappingRelation
object: These concept mapping relations mirror semantic relations, and the data model defined below is similar (with the exception of skos:exactMatch) to the data model defined for semantic relations. A distinct vocabulary is provided for concept mapping relations, to provide a convenient way to differentiate links within a concept scheme from links between concept schemes. However, this pattern of usage is not a formal requirement of the SKOS data model, and relies on informal definitions of best practice.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrowerTransitive
object: By convention, skos:narrowerTransitive is not used to make assertions. Rather, the properties can be used to draw inferences about the transitive closure of the hierarchical relation, which is useful e.g. when implementing a simple query expansion algorithm in a search application.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrower
object: Relates a concept to a concept that is more specific in meaning.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader
object: Broader concepts are typically rendered as parents in a concept hierarchy (tree).

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core
object: An RDF vocabulary for describing the basic structure and content of concept schemes such as thesauri, classification schemes, subject heading lists, taxonomies, 'folksonomies', other types of controlled vocabulary, and also concept schemes embedded in glossaries and terminologies.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrowerTransitive
object: skos:narrowerTransitive is a transitive superproperty of skos:narrower.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader
object: Relates a concept to a concept that is more general in meaning.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition
object: A statement or formal explanation of the meaning of a concept.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exactMatch
object: skos:exactMatch is used to link two concepts, indicating a high degree of confidence that the concepts can be used interchangeably across a wide range of information retrieval applications. skos:exactMatch is a transitive property, and is a sub-property of skos:closeMatch.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#memberList
object:
For any resource, every item in the list given as the value of the
      skos:memberList property is also a value of the skos:member property.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core
object: Participants in W3C's Semantic Web Deployment Working Group.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#changeNote
object: A note about a modification to a concept.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#altLabel
object: skos:prefLabel, skos:altLabel and skos:hiddenLabel are pairwise disjoint properties.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#semanticRelation
object: This property should not be used directly, but as a super-property for all properties denoting a relationship of meaning between concepts.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#hiddenLabel
object: skos:prefLabel, skos:altLabel and skos:hiddenLabel are pairwise disjoint properties.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel
object: The preferred lexical label for a resource, in a given language.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#hiddenLabel
object: The range of skos:hiddenLabel is the class of RDF plain literals.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel
object: A resource has no more than one value of skos:prefLabel per language tag, and no more than one value of skos:prefLabel without language tag.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#inScheme
object: A concept may be a member of more than one concept scheme.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#inScheme
object: Relates a resource (for example a concept) to a concept scheme in which it is included.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#semanticRelation
object: Links a concept to a concept related by meaning.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#ConceptScheme
object: A set of concepts, optionally including statements about semantic relationships between those concepts.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#altLabel
object: Acronyms, abbreviations, spelling variants, and irregular plural/singular forms may be included among the alternative labels for a concept. Mis-spelled terms are normally included as hidden labels (see skos:hiddenLabel).

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broaderTransitive
object: By convention, skos:broaderTransitive is not used to make assertions. Rather, the properties can be used to draw inferences about the transitive closure of the hierarchical relation, which is useful e.g. when implementing a simple query expansion algorithm in a search application.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#notation
object: By convention, skos:notation is used with a typed literal in the object position of the triple.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrowMatch
object: skos:narrowMatch is used to state a hierarchical mapping link between two conceptual resources in different concept schemes.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#notation
object: A notation, also known as classification code, is a string of characters such as "T58.5" or "303.4833" used to uniquely identify a concept within the scope of a given concept scheme.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote
object: A note that helps to clarify the meaning and/or the use of a concept.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#OrderedCollection
object: An ordered collection of concepts, where both the grouping and the ordering are meaningful.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broadMatch
object: skos:broadMatch is used to state a hierarchical mapping link between two conceptual resources in different concept schemes.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#mappingRelation
object: Relates two concepts coming, by convention, from different schemes, and that have comparable meanings

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#hasTopConcept
object: Relates, by convention, a concept scheme to a concept which is topmost in the broader/narrower concept hierarchies for that scheme, providing an entry point to these hierarchies.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Collection
object: Labelled collections can be used where you would like a set of concepts to be displayed under a 'node label' in the hierarchy.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#topConceptOf
object: Relates a concept to the concept scheme that it is a top level concept of.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#editorialNote
object: A note for an editor, translator or maintainer of the vocabulary.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrower
object: By convention, skos:broader is only used to assert an immediate (i.e. direct) hierarchical link between two conceptual resources.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#hiddenLabel
object: A lexical label for a resource that should be hidden when generating visual displays of the resource, but should still be accessible to free text search operations.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#memberList
object: Relates an ordered collection to the RDF list containing its members.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel
object: The range of skos:prefLabel is the class of RDF plain literals.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example
object: An example of the use of a concept.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#closeMatch
object: skos:closeMatch is used to link two concepts that are sufficiently similar that they can be used interchangeably in some information retrieval applications. In order to avoid the possibility of "compound errors" when combining mappings across more than two concept schemes, skos:closeMatch is not declared to be a transitive property.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#member
object: Relates a collection to one of its members.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#altLabel
object: An alternative lexical label for a resource.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept
object: An idea or notion; a unit of thought.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broaderTransitive
object: skos:broaderTransitive is a transitive superproperty of skos:broader.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#altLabel
object: The range of skos:altLabel is the class of RDF plain literals.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#relatedMatch
object: skos:relatedMatch is used to state an associative mapping link between two conceptual resources in different concept schemes.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#ConceptScheme
object: A concept scheme may be defined to include concepts from different sources.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#ConceptScheme
object: Thesauri, classification schemes, subject heading lists, taxonomies, 'folksonomies', and other types of controlled vocabulary are all examples of concept schemes. Concept schemes are also embedded in glossaries and terminologies.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrower
object: Narrower concepts are typically rendered as children in a concept hierarchy (tree).

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader
object: By convention, skos:broader is only used to assert an immediate (i.e. direct) hierarchical link between two conceptual resources.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exactMatch
object: skos:exactMatch is disjoint with each of the properties skos:broadMatch and skos:relatedMatch.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel
object:
skos:prefLabel, skos:altLabel and skos:hiddenLabel are pairwise
      disjoint properties.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#related
object: Relates a concept to a concept with which there is an associative semantic relationship.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#OrderedCollection
object: Ordered collections can be used where you would like a set of concepts to be displayed in a specific order, and optionally under a 'node label'.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#note
object: This property may be used directly, or as a super-property for more specific note types.

subject: http://www.w3.org/ns/time/gregorian
object: The set of months-of-the-year from the Gregorian calendar.

subject: http://www.w3.org/ns/time/gregorian/January
object:
A _class_ with the local-name January was present in the 2006 version of OWL-Time. 
It was presented as an example of how DateTimeDescription could be specialized. 
In the 2017 version of OWL-Time that class is deprecated, but this individual provided instead, in a separate namespace.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalContains
object: If a proper interval T1 is intervalContains another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is before the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is after the end of T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#generalDay
object:
Day of month - formulated as a text string with a pattern constraint to reproduce the same lexical form as gDay, except that values up to 99 are permitted, in order to support calendars with more than 31 days in a month. 
Note that the value-space is not defined, so a generic OWL2 processor cannot compute ordering relationships of values of this type.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#inXSDDate
object: Position of an instant, expressed using xsd:date

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#generalYear
object:
Year number - formulated as a text string with a pattern constraint to reproduce the same lexical form as gYear, but not restricted to values from the Gregorian calendar. 
Note that the value-space is not defined, so a generic OWL2 processor cannot compute ordering relationships of values of this type.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalIn
object: Esta relacin entre intervalos no estaba incluida en las 13 relaciones bsicas definidas por Allen (1984), pero se hace referencia a ella como "una relacin importante" en Allen y Ferguson (1997). Es la unin disjunta de 'intervalo empieza', 'intervalo durante' y con 'intervalo termina'. Sin embargo, esto est fuera de la expresividad de OWL2, por tanto, se implementa como una propiedad explcita, con 'intervalo empieza', 'intervalo durante' e 'intervalo termina' como sub-propiedades.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#dayOfWeek
object: El da de la semana, cuyo valor es un miembro de la clase 'da de la semana'.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#hasXSDDuration
object: Feature at risk - added in 2017 revision, and not yet widely used.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalIn
object: If a proper interval T1 is intervalIn another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the beginning of T2 or is coincident with the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is before the end of T2, or is coincident with the end of T2, except that end of T1 may not be coincident with the end of T2 if the beginning of T1 is coincident with the beginning of T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#hasXSDDuration
object: Extensin de una entidad temporal, expresada utilizando xsd:duration.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#year
object:
Year position in a calendar-clock system.

The range of this property is not specified, so can be replaced by any specific representation of a calendar year from any calendar.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#generalMonth
object:
Mes del ao - formulado como una cadena de texto con una restriccin patrn para reproducir la misma forma lxica que gMonth, excepto que se permiten valores hasta el 20, con el propsito de proporcionar soporte a calendarios con aos con ms de 12 meses.
            Ntese que el espacio de valores no est definido, por tanto, un procesador genrico de OWL2 no puede computar relaciones de orden de valores de este tipo.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#TemporalDuration
object: Time extent; duration of a time interval separate from its particular start position

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#inXSDDateTime
object: Position of an instant, expressed using xsd:dateTime

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#dayOfWeek
object: The day of week, whose value is a member of the class time:DayOfWeek

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalOverlaps
object: Si un intervalo propio T1 se solapa con otro intervalo propio T2, entonces el principio de T1 es anterior al principio de T2, el final de T1 es posterior al principio de T2, y el final de T1 es anterior al final de T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#ProperInterval
object: A temporal entity with non-zero extent or duration, i.e. for which the value of the beginning and end are different

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#hasXSDDuration
object: Caracterstica arriesgada - aadida en la revisin de 2017, y todava no ampliamente utilizada.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#TimeZone
object:
Un huso horario designado est asociado con una regin geogrfica. Sin embargo, para una regin particular el desplazamiento desde UTC a menudo vara segn las estaciones, y las fechas de los cambios pueden variar de un ao a otro. La designacin de huso horario  normalmente cambia de una estacin a otra (por ejemplo, el horario estndar frente al horario de verano ambos del este de Australia). Adems, del desplazamiento para un huso horario puede cambiar sobre escalas de tiempo mayores, aunque su designacin no lo haga.
    Se puede encontrar una gua detallada sobre el funcionamiento de husos horarios en http://www.w3.org/TR/timezone/."@es , "En [owl-time-20060927] se describi una ontologa para descripciones de husos horarios, y se proporcion en un espacio de nombres separado tzont:. Sin embargo, dicha ontologa estaba incompleta en su alcance, y el ejemplo de conjuntos de datos (datasets) era selectivo. Adems, puesto que el uso de una clase de una ontologa externa como el rango de una propiedad de objeto en OWL-Time crea una dependencia, la referencia a la clase huso horario se ha reemplazado por una clase que viene a ser un "cajn de sastre" en la en la parte normativa de esta versin de OWL-Time.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#generalYear
object:
Nmero de ao - formulado como una cadena de texto con una restriccin patrn para reproducir la misma forma lxica que gYear, aunque no est restringido a valores del calendario gregoriano.
            Ntese que el espacio de valores no est definido, por tanto, un procesador genrico de OWL2 no puede computar relaciones de orden de valores de este tipo.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#inTimePosition
object: Posicin de un instante, expresada como una coordenada temporal o un valor nominal.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalMeets
object: If a proper interval T1 is intervalMeets another proper interval T2, then the end of T1 is coincident with the beginning of T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#before
object: Asume una direccin en el tiempo. Si una entidad temporal T1 est antes que otra entidad temporal T2, entonces el final de T1 est antes que el principio de T2. As, "antes" se puede considerar bsica para instantes y derivada para intervalos.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#DurationDescription
object: In the Gregorian calendar the length of the month is not fixed. Therefore, a value like "2.5 months" cannot be exactly compared with a similar duration expressed in terms of weeks or days.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#minute
object: Minute position in a calendar-clock system.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#week
object: Las semanas estn numeradas de forma diferente dependiendo del calendario en uso y de las convenciones lingsticas y culturales locales (locale en ingls). El ISO-8601 especifica que la primera semana del ao incluye al menos cuatro das, y que el lunes es el primer da de la semana. En ese sistema, la semana 1 es la semana que contiene el primer jueves del ao.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#inXSDDateTime
object: Posicin de un instante, expresado utilizando xsd:dateTime.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#GeneralDateTimeDescription
object: Descripcin de fecha y hora estructurada con valores separados para los distintos elementos de un sistema calendario-reloj.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalDisjoint
object: If a proper interval T1 is intervalDisjoint another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the end of T2, or the end of T1 is before the beginning of T2, i.e. the intervals do not overlap in any way, but their ordering relationship is not known.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#TimeZone
object:
Un huso horario especifica la cantidad en que la hora local est desplazada con respecto a UTC.
    Un huso horario normalmente se denota geogrficamente (p.ej. el horario de verano del este de Australia), con un valor constante en una regin dada.
    La regin donde aplica y el desplazamiento desde UTC las especifica una autoridad gubernamental localmente reconocida.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#GeneralDurationDescription
object: Description of temporal extent structured with separate values for the various elements of a calendar-clock system.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#MonthOfYear
object: La pertenencia a la clase 'mes del ao' est abierta, a permitir calendarios anuales alternativos y diferentes nombres de meses.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#GeneralDateTimeDescription
object: Description of date and time structured with separate values for the various elements of a calendar-clock system

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Duration
object: Alternative to time:DurationDescription to support description of a temporal duration other than using a calendar/clock system.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#inXSDgYearMonth
object: Posicin de un instante, expresado utilizando xsd:gYearMonth.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#DurationDescription
object: En el calendario gregoriano la longitud de los meses no es fija. Por lo tanto, un valor como "2,5 meses" no se puede comparar exactamente con una duracin similar expresada en trminos de semanas o das.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#TRS
object:
A temporal reference system, such as a temporal coordinate system (with an origin, direction, and scale), a calendar-clock combination, or a (possibly hierarchical) ordinal system. 

This is a stub class, representing the set of all temporal reference systems.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalOverlaps
object: If a proper interval T1 is intervalOverlaps another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is before the beginning of T2, the end of T1 is after the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is before the end of T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#month
object:
Month position in a calendar-clock system.

The range of this property is not specified, so can be replaced by any specific representation of a calendar month from any calendar.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Duration
object: Duration of a temporal extent expressed as a number scaled by a temporal unit

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#nominalPosition
object: The (nominal) value indicating temporal position in an ordinal reference system

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#hasTRS
object: The temporal reference system used by a temporal position or extent description.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalFinishedBy
object: If a proper interval T1 is intervalFinishedBy another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is before the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is coincident with the end of T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#minutes
object: Longitud de, o elemento de la longitud de, una extensin temporal expresada en minutos.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#dayOfYear
object: El nmero de da en el ao.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#monthOfYear
object: Feature at risk - added in 2017 revision, and not yet widely used.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#TRS
object:
Un sistema de referencia temporal, tal como un sistema de coordenadas temporales (con un origen, una direccin y una escala), una combinacin calendario-reloj, o un sistema ordinal (posiblemente jerrquico).
        Esta clase comodn representa el conjunto de todos los sistemas de referencia temporal.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time
object: 2016-06-15 - initial update of OWL-Time - modified to support arbitrary temporal reference systems.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalStarts
object: Si un intervalo propio T1 empieza otro intervalo propio T2, entonces del principio de T1 con el principio de T2, y el final de T1 es anterior al final de T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalStartedBy
object: Si un intervalo propio T1 es empezado por otro intervalo propio T2, entonces el principio de T1 coincide con el principio de T2, y el final de T1 es posterior al final de T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#minute
object: Posicin de minuto en un sistema calendario-reloj.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#monthOfYear
object: Caracterstica arriesgada - aadida en la revisin de 2017, y todava no ampliamente utilizada.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#GeneralDurationDescription
object: Descripcin de extensin temporal estructurada con valores separados para los distintos elementos de un sistema de horario-calendario.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#day
object: Posicin de da en un sistema calendario-reloj.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#unitType
object: La unidad de tiempo que proporciona la precisin de un valor fecha-hora o la escala de una extensin temporal.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#hasDateTimeDescription
object: Valor de intervalo de fecha-hora expresado como un valor estructurado. El principio y el final del intervalo coincide con los lmites del elemento ms corto en la descripcin.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Duration
object: Duracin de una extensin temporal expresada como un nmero escalado por una unidad temporal.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#hasTime
object: Feature at risk - added in 2017 revision, and not yet widely used.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#xsdDateTime
object: Valor de 'intervalo de fecha-hora' expresado como un valor compacto.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Interval
object: A temporal entity with an extent or duration

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalBefore
object: Si un intervalo propio T1 est antes que otro intervalo propio T2, entonces el final de T1 est antes que el principio de T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalStarts
object: If a proper interval T1 is intervalStarts another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is coincident with the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is before the end of T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#hour
object: Hour position in a calendar-clock system.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#TimePosition
object: Una posicin temporal descrita utilizando bien un valor (nominal) de un sistema de referencia ordinal, o un valor (numrico) en un sistema de coordenadas temporales.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time
object:
Update of OWL-Time ontology, extended to support general temporal reference systems. 

Ontology engineering by Simon J D Cox

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#hasTRS
object: El sistema de referencia temporal utilizado por una posicin temporal o descripcin de extensin.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#inDateTime
object: Position of an instant, expressed using a structured description

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#hasTime
object: Caracterstica arriesgada -aadida en la revisin del 2017 que no ha sido todava utilizada de forma amplia.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#minutes
object: length, or element of, a temporal extent expressed in minutes

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#TemporalDuration
object: Time extent; duration of a time interval separate from its particular start position

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#inXSDDateTime
object: La propiedad 'en fecha-hora XSD' ha sido reemplazada por 'en fecha-sello de tiempo XSD' que hace obligatorio el campo 'huso horario'.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#months

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#GeneralDurationDescription
object: The extent of a time duration expressed as a GeneralDurationDescription depends on the Temporal Reference System. In some calendars the length of the week or month is not constant within the year. Therefore, a value like "2.5 months" may not necessarily be exactly compared with a similar duration expressed in terms of weeks or days. When non-earth-based calendars are considered even more care must be taken in comparing durations.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#month

Posicin de mes en un sistema calendario-reloj.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#TemporalDuration
object: Extensin de tiempo; duracin de un intervalo de tiempo independiente de su posicin de inicio particular.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#hasDuration
object: Duracin de una entidad temporal, evento o actividad, o cosa, expresada como un valor escalado.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#TemporalUnit
object: Membership of the class TemporalUnit is open, to allow for other temporal units used in some technical applications (e.g. millions of years, Baha'i month).

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#months

l rango de esta propiedad no est especificado, por tanto, se puede reemplazar por cualquier representacin especfica de un ao de calendario de un calendario cualquiera.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#week

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalFinishes
object: Si un intervalo propio T1 termina otro intervalo propio T2, entonces del principio de T1 est despus del principio de T2, y el final de T1 coincide con el final de T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#before
object: Gives directionality to time. If a temporal entity T1 is before another temporal entity T2, then the end of T1 is before the beginning of T2. Thus, "before" can be considered to be basic to instants and derived for intervals.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#inXSDDateTime
object: Position of an instant, expressed using xsd:dateTime

Day position in a calendar-clock system.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#inXSDgYear
object: Position of an instant, expressed using xsd:gYear

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalDuring
object: Si un intervalo propio T1 est durante otro intervalo propio T2, entonces del principio de T1 est despus del principio de T2, y el final de T1 est antes que el final de T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalFinishedBy
object: If a proper interval T1 is intervalFinishedBy another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is before the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is coincident with the end of T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalMetBy
object: Si un intervalo propio T1 es 'intervalo encontrado por' otro intervalo propio T2, entonces el principio de T1 coincide con el final de T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#numericDuration

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#inDateTime
object: Posicin de un instante, expresada utilizando una descripcin estructurada.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalDuring
object: If a proper interval T1 is intervalDuring another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is before the end of T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#hasTime
object: Supports the association of a temporal entity (instant or interval) to any thing

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#before
object: Asume una direccin en el tiempo. Si una entidad temporal T1 est antes que otra entidad temporal T2, entonces el final de T1 est antes que el principio de T2. As, "antes" se puede considerar bsica para instantes y derivada para intervalos.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#DateTimeDescription
object: Description of date and time structured with separate values for the various elements of a calendar-clock system. The temporal reference system is fixed to Gregorian Calendar, and the range of year, month, day properties restricted to corresponding XML Schema types xsd:gYear, xsd:gMonth and xsd:gDay, respectively.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalIn
object: This interval relation is not included in the 13 basic relationships defined in Allen (1984), but is referred to as 'an important relationship' in Allen and Ferguson (1997). It is the disjoint union of :intervalStarts v :intervalDuring v :intervalFinishes . However, that is outside OWL2 expressivity, so is implemented as an explicit property, with :intervalStarts , :intervalDuring , :intervalFinishes as sub-properties

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalStartedBy
object: Si un intervalo propio T1 es empezado por otro intervalo propio T2, entonces el principio de T1 coincide con el principio de T2, y el final de T1 es posterior al final de T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#TimeZone
object:
A designated timezone is associated with a geographic region. However, for a particular region the offset from UTC often varies seasonally, and the dates of the changes may vary from year to year. The timezone designation usually changes for the different seasons (e.g. Australian Eastern Standard Time vs. Australian Eastern Daylight Time). Furthermore, the offset for a timezone may change over longer timescales, though its designation might not.  

Detailed guidance about working with time zones is given in http://www.w3.org/TR/timezone/ .

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Instant
object: Una entidad temporal con una extensin o duracin cero.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#hasDurationDescription
object: Duracin de una entidad temporal, expresada utilizando una descripcin estructurada.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#after
object: Asume una direccin en el tiempo. Si una entidad temporal T1 est despus de otra entidad temporal T2, entonces el principio de T1 est despus del final de T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#after
object: Gives directionality to time. If a temporal entity T1 is after another temporal entity T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the end of T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Year
object:
Year was proposed in the 2006 version of OWL-Time as an example of how DurationDescription could be specialized to allow for a duration to be restricted to a number of years. 

It is deprecated in this edition of OWL-Time.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalMetBy
object: If a proper interval T1 is intervalMetBy another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is coincident with the end of T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Duration
object: Duration of a temporal extent expressed as a number scaled by a temporal unit

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#hour
object: Posicin de hora en un sistema calendario-reloj.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalIn
object: Si un intervalo propio T1 es un intervalo interior a otro intervalo propio T2, entonces el principio de T1 est despus del principio de T2 o coincide con el principio de T2, y el final de T1 est antes que el final de T2, o coincide con el final de T2, excepto que el final de T1 puede no coincidir con el final de T2 si el principio de T1 coincide con el principio de T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalAfter
object: Si un intervalo propio T1 es posterior a otro intervalo propio T2, entonces el principio de T1 est despus que el final de T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#minutes

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#inTemporalPosition
object: Posicin de un instante de tiempo.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#generalDay
object:
Day of month - formulated as a text string with a pattern constraint to reproduce the same lexical form as gDay, except that values up to 99 are permitted, in order to support calendars with more than 31 days in a month. 
Note that the value-space is not defined, so a generic OWL2 processor cannot compute ordering relationships of values of this type.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Interval
object: A temporal entity with an extent or duration

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalFinishedBy
object: Si un intervalo propio T1 est terminado por otro intervalo propio T2, entonces el principio de T1 est antes que el principio de T2, y el final de T1 coincide con el final de T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalAfter
object: If a proper interval T1 is intervalAfter another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the end of T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#timeZone
object:
In the original 2006 version of OWL-Time, the range of time:timeZone was a TimeZone class in a separate namespace "http://www.w3.org/2006/timezone#". 
An alignment axiom 
	tzont:TimeZone rdfs:subClassOf time:TimeZone . 
allows data encoded according to the previous version to be consistent with the updated ontology.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalEquals
object: If a proper interval T1 is intervalEquals another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is coincident with the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is coincident with the end of T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#inXSDDateTimeStamp
object: Posicin de un instante, expresado utilizando xsd:dateTimeStamp.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#GeneralDurationDescription
object: Descripcin de extensin temporal estructurada con valores separados para los distintos elementos de un sistema de horario-calendario.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#hasDateTimeDescription
object: Valor de intervalo de fecha-hora expresado como un valor estructurado. El principio y el final del intervalo coincide con los lmites del elemento ms corto en la descripcin.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Duration
object: Duracin de una extensin temporal expresada como un nmero escalado por una unidad temporal.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalContains
object: Si un intervalo propio T1 contiene otro intervalo propio T2, entonces el principio de T1 est antes que el principio de T2, y el final de T1 est despus del final de T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#numericPosition
object: The (numeric) value indicating position within a temporal coordinate system

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#TemporalDuration

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#generalDay
object:
Da del mes - formulado como una cadena de texto con una restriccin patrn para reproducir la misma forma lxica que gDay, excepto que se permiten valores hasta el 99, con el propsito de proporcionar soporte a calendarios con meses con ms de 31 das.
            Ntese que el espacio de valores no est definido, por tanto, un procesador genrico de OWL2 no puede computar relaciones de orden de valores de este tipo.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#generalMonth
object:
Mes del ao - formulado como una cadena de texto con una restriccin patrn para reproducir la misma forma lxica que gMonth, excepto que se permiten valores hasta el 20, con el propsito de proporcionar soporte a calendarios con aos con ms de 12 meses.
            Ntese que el espacio de valores no est definido, por tanto, un procesador genrico de OWL2 no puede computar relaciones de orden de valores de este tipo.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#inXSDDate

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#TimeZone
object:
A Time Zone specifies the amount by which the local time is offset from UTC. 
	A time zone is usually denoted geographically (e.g. Australian Eastern Daylight Time), with a constant value in a given region. 
The region where it applies and the offset from UTC are specified by a locally recognised governing authority.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#minutes

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#hour

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#DateTimeInterval
object: 'intervalo de fecha-hora' es una subclase de 'intervalo propio', definida utilizando el multi-elemento 'descripcin de fecha-hora'.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#GeneralDateTimeDescription
object: Algunas combinaciones de propiedades son redundantes - por ejemplo, dentro de un 'ao' especificado si se proporciona 'da del ao' entonces 'da' y 'mes' se pueden computar, y viceversa. Los valores individuales deberan ser consistentes entre ellos y con el calendario, indicado a travs del valor de la propiedad 'tiene TRS'.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#hasDurationDescription
object: Duration of a temporal entity, expressed using a structured description

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#days

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#TimePosition

object: Si un intervalo propio T1 est terminado por otro intervalo propio T2, entonces el principio de T1 est antes que el principio de T2, y el final de T1 coincide con el final de T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#DateTimeDescription
object: Descripcin de fecha y tiempo estructurada con valores separados para los diferentes elementos de un sistema calendario-reloj. subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#DateTimeInterval
object: DateTimeInterval is a subclass of ProperInterval, defined using the multi-element DateTimeDescription.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#monthOfYear

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#day

Day position in a calendar-clock system.

The range of this property is not specified, so can be replaced by any specific representation of a calendar day from any calendar.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#days
object: Longitud de, o elemento de la longitud de, una extensin temporal expresada en das.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalAfter
object: Si un intervalo propio T1 es posterior a otro intervalo propio T2, entonces el principio de T1 est despus que el final de T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#TimeZone
object:
In the original 2006 version of OWL-Time, the TimeZone class, with several properties corresponding to a specific model of time-zones, was defined in a separate namespace "http://www.w3.org/2006/timezone#". 

In the current version a class with same local name is put into the main OWL-Time namespace, removing the dependency on the external namespace. 

An alignment axiom 
	tzont:TimeZone rdfs:subClassOf time:TimeZone . 
allows data encoded according to the previous version to be consistent with the updated ontology.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalOverlappedBy
object: Si un intervalo propio T1 es 'intervalo solapado por' otro intervalo propio T2, entonces el principio de T1 es posterior al principio de T2, y el principio de T1 es anterior al final de T2, y el final de T1 es posterior al final de T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#inXSDDateTimeStamp

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#TimeZone

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Interval
object: Una entidad temporal con una extensin o duracin.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#TemporalEntity

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#DateTimeInterval
object: :DateTimeInterval can only be used for an interval whose limits coincide with a date-time element aligned to the calendar and timezone indicated. For example, while both have a duration of one day, the 24-hour interval beginning at midnight at the beginning of 8 May in Central Europe can be expressed as a :DateTimeInterval, but the 24-hour interval starting at 1:30pm cannot.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalDisjoint
object: Si un intervalo propio T1 es disjunto con otro intervalo propio T2, entonces el principio de T1 est despus del final de T2, o el final de T1 est antes que el principio de T2, es decir, los intervalos no se solapan de ninguna forma, aunque su relacin de orden no se conozca.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#GeneralDateTimeDescription

object: 2017-02 - intervalIn, intervalDisjoint, monthOfYear added; TemporalUnit subclass of TemporalDuration

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#intervalOverlappedBy
object: If a proper interval T1 is intervalOverlappedBy another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the beginning of T2, the beginning of T1 is before the end of T2, and the end of T1 is after the end of T2.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#TimeZone
object: An ontology for time zone descriptions was described in [owl-time-20060927] and provided as RDF in a separate namespace tzont:. However, that ontology was incomplete in scope, and the example datasets were selective. Furthermore, since the use of a class from an external ontology as the range of an ObjectProperty in OWL-Time creates a dependency, reference to the time zone class has been replaced with the 'stub' class in the normative part of this version of OWL-Time.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#inside

object: Longitud de, o elemento de la longitud de, una extensin temporal expresada en horas.

object: Membership of the class :MonthOfYear is open, to allow for alternative annual calendars and different month names.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#TemporalUnit
object: Una duracin estndar, que proporciona un factor de escala para una extensin de tiempo, o la granularidad o precisin para una posicin de tiempo.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#TRS
